''Theorem.''
Let $$f\colon \R \times \R^n \supset \Omega \to \R^n$$ be locally Lipschitz w.r.t. $$x$$ and let $$x\colon \openI{t_-,t_+} \to \R^n$$ be a maximal Solution of $$\dot{x} = f(t,x).$$ Then either

* $$t_+=+\infty$$ or
* $$t_+<+\infty$$ and $$x(t)$$ explodes at $$t=t_+,$$ i.e. for any compact set $$K \subseteq \Omega$$ there exists $$t'<t_+$$ such that $$(t,x(t)) \notin K$$ for all $$t \in \openI{t',t_+}.$$

